    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>3</m> or <m>4</m> learners
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials needed:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A <m>15</m> or <m>30</m> cm ruler
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A small stone or a piece of paper rolled into a tight ball
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A small, hollow object (like a key ring or a circular slice cut from a plastic pen cap)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                In your groups:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Place your ruler flat on the desk. This will be your number line.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Place the small stone/rolled paper ball at the point representing <m>0</m> on your ruler (the number line).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Place the hollow object at the point representing <m>3</m> on your ruler (the number line).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                     <li>
                        <p>
                            Move the stone/rolled paper ball to represent all the numbers that satisfy the inequality <m>x \gt 3</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Move the stone/rolled paper ball to represent all the numbers that satisfy the inequality <m>x \le -2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Move the stone/rolled paper ball to represent all the numbers that satisfy the inequality <m>2x + 3 \lt 7</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss how you represented the solution to each inequality on your number line.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your representations and descriptions with the class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
            <p>
                For <m>x \gt 3</m>, place the hollow object at <m>3</m> and move the stone/rolled paper ball to the right of it to represent all numbers greater than <m>3</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                For <m>x \le -2</m>, place the hollow object at <m>-2</m> and move the stone/rolled paper ball to the left of it to represent all numbers less than or equal to <m>-2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                For <m>2x + 3 \lt 7</m>, first solve the inequality to find that <m>x \lt 2</m>. Then place the hollow object at <m>2</m> and move the stone/rolled paper ball to the left of it to represent all numbers less than <m>2</m>.
            </p>
        </hint>
    </activity>

    <insight>
        <p>
            Graphing an inequality in one unknown means representing every number that satisfies the inequality on a number line.
        </p>
        <p>
            A strict inequality, such as <m>x \gt 3</m>, uses an open circle at <m>3</m> and shades(bolds) the number line to the right. An inclusive inequality, such as <m>x \le -2</m>, uses a closed circle at <m>-2</m> and shades to the left.
        </p>
        <p>
            To graph an inequality like <m>2x + 3 \lt 7</m>, first solve the inequality to find the boundary point (in this case, <m>x \lt 2</m>), then graph it using the appropriate circle and shading.
        </p>
        <p>
            Graphing inequalities helps us visualize the set of solutions and understand the relationships between different inequalities.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Graph <m>x \gt 6</m> on a number line.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <image xml:id="img-inequality-x-greater-6" width="70%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % 1. Draw the main number line axis with arrows on both ends
                            \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick] (2,0) -- (10,0);
                            % 2. Draw the tick marks and the numbers below them
                            \foreach \x in {3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9} {
                                \draw (\x, 0.12) -- (\x, -0.12) node[below] {$\x$};
                            }

                            % 3. Draw the thick line for the inequality pointing to the right
                            \draw[->, ultra thick] (6.1,0) -- (9.5,0);

                            % 4. Draw the OPEN circle at x = 6
                            \filldraw[fill=white, draw=black, thick] (6,0) circle (3pt);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Graph <m>x \le -3</m> on a number line.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the following inequality and represent the solution on a graph:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x + 3 \amp \lt 7</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We start by solving the inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x + 3 \amp \lt 7</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x \amp \lt 4</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp \lt 2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

